Judges propose protection from presidents
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (HRC), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts and to introduce their election.
For the Courts of Appeal and Cassation, the HRC wishes to introduce special districts that will not be linked to the administrative and territorial division of the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential mandate.
The HRC has finalized proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
The HRC carried out this work on behalf of Vladimir Putin, dated 3 January 2017, which the President gave after meeting with members of the Council.
A meeting with Council members on 8 December 2016 included individual cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as issues of public control in places of detention of citizens (see “Happily” of 9 December).
As a result of the work of the HRC, 25 proposals have been made, covering both the independence of the judiciary and the identification of judicial errors, as well as the financing of the courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin human rights defenders is to restrict the powers of the presidents of the courts in order to enhance the independence of the remaining judges.
If a candidate for the position of judge has successfully been successful and has received the support of the judicial community, the President of the Court, according to the HRC, should submit him for appointment without the right to refuse, as the law now permits.
It is also proposed that the President should be deprived of the right to allocate cases to the judges.
This may be done by experts, perhaps by a specially written computer program.
In addition, the HRC considers that the President is not entitled “to determine the qualifications of the judge, initiate disciplinary proceedings and decide on additional material payments”.
In doing so, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to “election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves” and “to give them authority for a relatively short time with mandatory rotation”.
All presidents of the courts (from republican to district) are now appointed for six years by the President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from pressure from regional administrations, the HRC proposes a new appeal and appeal to the courts of general jurisdiction.
Their structure is now tied to the administrative and territorial division in the Russian Federation.
In the HRC, it is stated that “it is necessary to ensure that separate courts of appeal and Cassation are organized, not at the regional level, in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts”.
Experts base the practice of arbitration courts.
They have “judicial districts” that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but that guarantee greater independence from regional officials who are unable to use “telephone law”.
The Justices of the Peace of the HRC suggest strengthening the people's assessors to deal with certain “civil and administrative categories”.
For example, the deprivation of parental rights, the restoration of employment, the protection of honour and dignity, the deprivation of driving rights, etc.
“This is just our proposals”, explained a member of the HRC, a judge of the Constitutional Court retired by Tamar Morszczekov.
She also recalled that the President ' s mandate was not limited to the HRC, but also to the Supreme Court (HU), which had not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time for the military (among the co-defendants - the Office of the Attorney-General and the Human Rights Commissioner in the Russian Federation).
