Herrett told me that she had gained a better understanding of what her staff thought and felt in the three years she had used Glint.
In addition to the rapid surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a company's thermal map and shows in visual form which units have more complaints and which managers have a low validation rating, which allows them to understand why.
Companies realize little that they need to control the workplace, otherwise they'll become another Uber, which was involved in a scandal when a former staff member published a post on a blog describing an aggressive environment in which those who complained were punished.
For start-ups like Glint, it's a desire to control the situation, an opportunity for profitable business.
According to the Internet portal “Let's talk about payments”, dedicated to financial technology, the global governance, regulation and conformity industry could cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
Convercent startup from Denver, Colorado, which helps companies to prevent and detect misconduct, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year in the face of the fall in Hubert's reputation.
