And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go straight to the head office.
“The court of public opinion has taken over the authority of the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinn, founder and president of Convercent.
If it is found that the company has been mistreated by staff members or has acted immorally, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company may have costly consequences in the form of boycotts by clients, staff outflows and lawsuits, Quinn reported.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees in 500 institutions, has been using Convercent for over a year to ensure that staff are aware of the rules and procedures and to offer an easy way to approach the company's head office.
