Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help to ease the OVC.
Red meat and chocolate are commonly considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests the opposite: A diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help alleviate the symptoms of intestinal inflammation.
It is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, resulting in cripples and stomach swelling, chronic or blood loss, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Although meat and dairy products are usually recommended to alleviate symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid of the protein tryptofan contributes to the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
The leading researcher, Dr. Marco Colónna, explained that intestinal immune cells ensure that harmful microbes from food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of starting an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance while protecting the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
If the balance is too severe for inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory intestinal diseases.
The experiments showed that mice with a certain bacteria in their intestines have increased cell tolerance.
And this bacteria needs tryptofan, one of the building blocks of protein, to start these cells.
Professor Colonna said, "We've established a connection between one type of bacteria, Lactobaccillus reuteri, which is part of the normal intestinal microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more triptofane was contained in mice' diet, the more immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same would work for people: a combination of L. reuteri and triptofan-rich diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the intestine.
Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganvas, after studying the variety of immune cell tolerance, found that one group of test mice had these cells and another group that belonged to the same line but was kept separately, had no them.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by intestinal microbioms of mice, bacteria, viruses and fungi, which usually live in the stomach tract.
The DNA of the mouse intestine cells has been segregated and six types of bacteria present in mice that have immune cells but are missing from mice that do not have them have them have been detected.
Mice grown in a sterile environment without a good microbiomy and without developing this type of immune cell have been given L. reuteri, and they have immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers raised L. reuteri in the liquid environment and then transferred small amounts of fluid, without bacteria, to undeveloped immune cells released from mice.
Immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it proved to be a byproduct of triptofane processing known as indol-3-milic acid.
When researchers doubled the number of tryptofan into mice, the number of cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of tryptofan was halved, the number of cells also dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that people have cells that are as tolerant as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their stomach tract.
It is not known whether the byproducts of triptofane from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans as well as in mice, but in humans suffering from intestinal inflammatory intestinal diseases, defects were found in the genes associated with tryptofan.
She says, "Maybe we need to strengthen the development of these cells because these cells are dependent on inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines.
High levels of tryptofan, if available, may potentially increase their population.”
