The Russian Federation will have two new territories in advance of socio-economic development, “Abaza” and “Novotroitsk”.
The relevant regulations of the Government of the Russian Federation will enter into force today, 4 August.
The boundaries and economic activities of thetora in the territory of the town of Abaza in the Republic of Khakasia have been defined.
In a city of 15,000 people, there will be a special legal regime for entrepreneurship, as well as a minimum amount of capital investment for residents, a minimum number of new permanent jobs.
This is expected to attract some 2.5 billion roubles of investment into the city and to create more than 600 new jobs.
In the list of economic activities in which Abaza TOR will operate a special legal regime for business activities, such as crop production, livestock production, food production, nonalcoholic beverages and clothing.
Already, the Government of the Republic has signed framework agreements for the implementation of 8 investment projects.
It is also planned to reduce the dependence of the Territory on the SGS “Abakana Mining”.
In January 2017, the authorities in the region reported that Hakasia had fulfilled all the conditions of the Mineconom development for the establishment of the TNC.
The authorities in Orenburg have done the same.
There, the city of Novotroitsk will also establish a territory that is ahead of socio-economic development.
This would diversify the monogradal economy, reduce its dependence on the urban-based enterprise AO “Ural steel”, create more than 2,300 jobs and attract investment of more than 8 billion roubles.
The list of economic activities in which the new operator will have a special legal regime for entrepreneurs includes freshwater fishing, feed production, medicines and medical materials, among others.
Novotroitsk was the first of the monocitys of the Orenburg region to become an TOR.
We will recall that the pre-development area is an economic zone with favourable tax conditions, simplified administrative procedures and other privileges created to attract investment in improving the lives of the population.
Among the benefits for residents of the TAR are: a profit tax of not more than 5 per cent during the first five years and not less than 10 per cent over the next five years, social contributions of 7.6 per cent over 10 years, the use of a free customs zone, preferential access to various infrastructure facilities, and preferential rent rates.
